|In article <2j81vl$n80@cnn.motown.ge.com>,
|Peter C. Bosch, X3549 <pbosch@epi042.gesd> wrote:
|> I have seven wheels (circular buffers) with 3, 5, 7, 11, 13, 17, &
|> 23 positions on each, respectively.  Each position holds a random
|> number. [....]  I can optionally have an eighth wheel, containing a
|> password.
|
|Your description is written in such a way as to leave you a hole to
|squirm out of if someone says it's trivially breakable.
|
|Specifically, you have to explicitly say what is the KEY and what is
|the ALGORITHM before anyone can usefully evaluate this.
|
|

Is it unobvious that they are all *different* random numbers?  The algorithm,
I thought, was well described.  Naturally, S/W at either end will need to have
the same set of *different* random numbers.  So what's the hole?

I do not leave myself holes to "squirm out of". 
		(At least not intentionally.:-)

